# üìò SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

**SQLite** is a lightweight, serverless, self-contained, **ACID-compliant** relational database management system (RDBMS) embedded directly into the Android operating system. It is the de-facto standard persistence mechanism for structured data on mobile and embedded/IoT edge devices, accessed in Android via the `android.database.sqlite` API package.

In the context of the KTU 2024 syllabus (PBCIT604 ‚Äì Mobile Applications for IoT), SQLite serves as the **on-device data persistence layer** between the Android application and the IoT cloud/edge pipeline, allowing sensor data, device configurations, and user information to be stored locally without an active network connection.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Syllabus Highlight (KTU 2024 - Module 3):** The focus is on **persisting data locally** ‚Äî i.e., handling sensor reads, buffered telemetry, device metadata, and offline cache using `SQLiteOpenHelper`, `SQLiteDatabase`, `Cursor`, and `ContentValues`.

---

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy (Intuitive Overview)

Imagine you are operating a **weather-monitoring IoT station** placed in a remote farm. The station has a small, rugged tablet that collects temperature, humidity, and soil-moisture readings every 10 seconds. Internet connectivity is intermittent.

Now, ask yourself: *Where do the readings go when the network drops?*

| Real-World Element | SQLite Equivalent |
|---|---|
| A **locker / filing cabinet** inside the tablet | The **`.db` file** stored at `/data/data/<package>/databases/` |
| **Folders** for "Temperature Logs", "Device IDs", "User Profiles" | **Tables** (`CREATE TABLE temperature_log (...)`) |
| **Pre-printed forms** with columns like "Time, Value, Sensor_ID" | **Schema** (column definitions, data types) |
| A **registration clerk** who sets up the locker before first use | `SQLiteOpenHelper.onCreate()` |
| A **maintenance clerk** who upgrades the cabinet structure when needed | `SQLiteOpenHelper.onUpgrade()` |
| A **paper slip returned to you** with results of your query | A **Cursor** object |
| A **filled-in paper slip** you hand to the clerk to insert | A **ContentValues** object |

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Insight:** Unlike a heavy enterprise database (MySQL/PostgreSQL) that needs a separate server process, SQLite is **embedded inside the application process itself** ‚Äî making it zero-configuration, zero-administration, and ideal for resource-constrained IoT edge nodes.

---

## 1.3 Physical / Standard Metrics to Remember

- **Default database storage path:** `/data/data/<your.package.name>/databases/<dbname>.db`
- **Maximum database size:** Up to **140 TB** theoretically; practically **several GB** on Android.
- **Transaction model:** **ACID** (Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability).
- **Type affinity:** SQLite uses **dynamic typing** with **type affinity** rules (TEXT, INTEGER, REAL, BLOB, NUMERIC).
- **Library footprint:** ~**600 KB** compiled binary ‚Äî extremely small, ideal for IoT firmware and edge devices.

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# üìò SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 The Android SQLite Architecture (Logical Layers)

The persistence layer in Android is structured in **three concentric logical rings**:

**Layer 1 ‚Äî Application / Activity Layer**
- Your Java/Kotlin code calling `db.insert(...)`, `db.query(...)`, `db.update(...)`.

**Layer 2 ‚Äî Helper Layer (`SQLiteOpenHelper`)**
- Manages database **creation**, **versioning**, and **upgrade migration**.
- Implements two critical callbacks: `onCreate(SQLiteDatabase db)` and `onUpgrade(SQLiteDatabase db, int oldV, int newV)`.

**Layer 3 ‚Äî Native SQLite Engine (C library `libsqlite.so`)**
- Embedded inside `/system/lib/` of the Android OS.
- Executes the actual SQL statements and returns `Cursor` objects.

---

## 2.2 The Core Classes ‚Äî Operational Breakdown

### üîπ A. `SQLiteOpenHelper` (The Lifecycle Manager)

A helper class that abstracts the tedious steps of opening, creating, and upgrading the database. Key contract methods:

- **`onCreate(SQLiteDatabase db)`** ‚Üí Called **only once** when the `.db` file does not yet exist. You must execute your `CREATE TABLE` SQL here.
- **`onUpgrade(SQLiteDatabase db, int oldVersion, int newVersion)`** ‚Üí Called when `DATABASE_VERSION` constant is incremented. Used for schema migration (ALTER TABLE, CREATE new table + COPY data + DROP old).
- **`getWritableDatabase()`** ‚Üí Returns a `SQLiteDatabase` for read+write operations.
- **`getReadableDatabase()`** ‚Üí Returns a read-only instance if disk is full.

### üîπ B. `SQLiteDatabase` (The Engine Handle)

This object is the actual gateway to issue SQL commands. The CRUD operations are exposed as high-level methods:

- `insert(table, nullColumnHack, ContentValues values)` ‚Üí Returns row ID (`long`).
- `update(table, ContentValues values, whereClause, whereArgs)` ‚Üí Returns affected-row count.
- `delete(table, whereClause, whereArgs)` ‚Üí Returns affected-row count.
- `query(...)` (overloaded) ‚Üí Returns a `Cursor` for SELECT.
- `execSQL(String sql)` ‚Üí For raw DDL/DML (e.g., `CREATE TABLE`).
- `rawQuery(String sql, String[] args)` ‚Üí Returns `Cursor`.

### üîπ C. `ContentValues` (The "Form to Insert")

A `Map`-like container pairing column names (`String`) with values. Cannot hold a `null` key. Used for `insert()` and `update()`.

### üîπ D. `Cursor` (The "Result Slip")

A pointer to a row set returned by `query()`/`rawQuery()`. Iterated using:

- `moveToFirst()`, `moveToNext()`, `moveToLast()`, `moveToPosition(int)`.
- Data extracted with type-safe getters: `getString(col)`, `getInt(col)`, `getFloat(col)`, `getDouble(col)`, `getBlob(col)`.
- Always closed with `cursor.close()` to prevent memory leaks.
- **Required by KTU:** You must know `Cursor.getCount()`, `Cursor.getColumnIndex(name)`.

---

## 2.3 SQLite Data Types & Type Affinity (High-Yield for KTU)

SQLite has only **5 storage classes**, but columns can declare **type affinities** that guide storage:

| Declared Affinity | Recommended Java/Kotlin Type | Storage Class |
|---|---|---|
| `INTEGER` | `long`, `int` | 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, or 8 bytes |
| `TEXT` | `String` | UTF-8/UTF-16 string |
| `REAL` | `double`, `float` | 8-byte IEEE float |
| `BLOB` | `byte[]` | Binary large object |
| `NUMERIC` | `boolean`, `Date`, decimal | Auto-coerced |

> [!NOTE]
> **Booleans are stored as INTEGER 0/1. Dates are stored as TEXT (ISO 8601) or INTEGER (Unix epoch ms).** KTU exam questions frequently test this!

---

## 2.4 KTU Formula / API Cheat Sheet (Memorize This)

| Operation | SQL Syntax | Android API Equivalent |
|---|---|---|
| **Create Table** | `CREATE TABLE t (id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, name TEXT);` | `db.execSQL(...)` inside `onCreate()` |
| **Insert** | `INSERT INTO t (name) VALUES ('A');` | `db.insert("t", null, cv)` |
| **Read All** | `SELECT * FROM t;` | `Cursor c = db.rawQuery("SELECT * FROM t", null);` |
| **Conditional Read** | `SELECT * FROM t WHERE id=?;` | `db.query("t", null, "id=?", new String[]{id}, null, null, null);` |
| **Update** | `UPDATE t SET name='B' WHERE id=1;` | `db.update("t", cv, "id=?", new String[]{"1"});` |
| **Delete** | `DELETE FROM t WHERE id=1;` | `db.delete("t", "id=?", new String[]{"1"});` |
| **Transaction** | `BEGIN; ... COMMIT;` | `db.beginTransaction(); ... db.setTransactionSuccessful(); db.endTransaction();` |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Android Special Constants:** A `null` value passed in `whereArgs` is replaced with the SQL keyword `NULL` automatically. Use `?` placeholders to prevent **SQL injection** ‚Äî a frequently asked KTU viva question.

---

## 2.5 Real-World IoT Utility

- **Offline buffer for sensor telemetry** ‚Äî sensor data stored on-device, then flushed to cloud when MQTT/HTTP becomes available.
- **Local device registry** ‚Äî list of paired BLE/Wi-Fi IoT devices, their MAC addresses, last-seen timestamps.
- **Configuration persistence** ‚Äî storing thresholds, calibration constants, alert rules.
- **Historical analytics** ‚Äî daily/weekly aggregations rendered on-device without server round-trip.
- **Login credentials and authentication tokens** for IoT gateways.

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# üìò SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Implementation Walkthrough (Exhaustive)

Since this is an implementation-heavy topic under a CS/IoT course, we walk through a complete IoT-flavoured SQLite example: **building a local cache for IoT sensor readings** (temperature, humidity, timestamp). Each line is explained.

---

## 3.1 Step 1 ‚Äî Define the Schema (Constants Block)

We first declare a Java class that holds schema constants. This separates design from logic ‚Äî a best-practice KTU expects.

**File: `SensorDbContract.java`**

```java
public final class SensorDbContract {

    // Outer class to prevent accidental instantiation
    private SensorDbContract() {}

    // === Inner class describing the "sensor_readings" table ===
    public static class SensorReading implements BaseColumns {

        public static final String TABLE_NAME       = "sensor_readings";
        public static final String COLUMN_ID        = "_id";       // Auto-increment PK
        public static final String COLUMN_SENSOR_ID = "sensor_id"; // Foreign ref e.g. "TEMP_01"
        public static final String COLUMN_TYPE      = "type";      // TEMP / HUMIDITY / SOIL
        public static final String COLUMN_VALUE     = "value";     // REAL reading
        public static final String COLUMN_TIMESTAMP = "timestamp"; // INTEGER (Unix ms)

        // Full CREATE TABLE statement as a single string
        public static final String SQL_CREATE_TABLE =
            "CREATE TABLE " + TABLE_NAME + " (" +
                COLUMN_ID        + " INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, " +
                COLUMN_SENSOR_ID + " TEXT NOT NULL, " +
                COLUMN_TYPE      + " TEXT NOT NULL, " +
                COLUMN_VALUE     + " REAL NOT NULL, " +
                COLUMN_TIMESTAMP + " INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0" +
            ");";

        // DROP statement for re-creation
        public static final String SQL_DROP_TABLE =
            "DROP TABLE IF EXISTS " + TABLE_NAME + ";";
    }
}
```

**Explanation of each line:**

- `final` class + private constructor ‚Üí cannot be subclassed or instantiated; it's a pure namespace holder.
- Implementing `BaseColumns` (Android contract) gives you a free standard `_id` column naming ‚Äî many Android adapters (`CursorAdapter`) rely on it.
- `AUTOINCREMENT` ensures the `_id` never reuses a deleted slot (unlike plain `INTEGER PRIMARY KEY`).
- The `CREATE TABLE` SQL is a **constant string** so `onCreate()` can simply `execSQL(...)` it.

---

## 3.2 Step 2 ‚Äî Build the Helper (`SQLiteOpenHelper`)

**File: `SensorDbHelper.java`**

```java
public class SensorDbHelper extends SQLiteOpenHelper {

    // If you change the schema, you MUST bump this version.
    public static final int    DATABASE_VERSION = 2;
    public static final String DATABASE_NAME    = "iot_sensor_cache.db";

    public SensorDbHelper(Context context) {
        super(context, DATABASE_NAME, null, DATABASE_VERSION);
    }

    // Called the FIRST time the .db file is created.
    @Override
    public void onCreate(SQLiteDatabase db) {
        db.execSQL(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.SQL_CREATE_TABLE);

        // Seed with one starter row (optional).
        ContentValues seed = new ContentValues();
        seed.put(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_SENSOR_ID, "BOOTSTRAP");
        seed.put(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_TYPE,      "INFO");
        seed.put(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_VALUE,     0.0);
        seed.put(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_TIMESTAMP,
                 System.currentTimeMillis());
        db.insert(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.TABLE_NAME, null, seed);
    }

    // Called whenever DATABASE_VERSION is increased.
    @Override
    public void onUpgrade(SQLiteDatabase db, int oldVersion, int newVersion) {
        // For production: copy data ‚Üí new table ‚Üí drop old. Here, simple drop.
        db.execSQL(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.SQL_DROP_TABLE);
        onCreate(db);
    }
}
```

**Explanation of each step:**

- The constructor delegates to `SQLiteOpenHelper`'s base constructor, passing the **DB filename**, a custom factory (`null` = default), and the **version int**.
- `onCreate()` runs in a **transaction automatically** ‚Äî so either all your DDL succeeds or none does.
- Bumping `DATABASE_VERSION` from `1 ‚Üí 2` triggers `onUpgrade(oldV=1, newV=2)` **only on devices that already have a v1 file**; on fresh installs, only `onCreate()` runs.
- The seed insert demonstrates how to populate default data safely during cold-start.

---

## 3.3 Step 3 ‚Äî INSERT (Persisting a Sensor Reading)

```java
public long insertReading(SQLiteDatabase db,
                          String sensorId,
                          String type,
                          double value) {

    ContentValues values = new ContentValues();
    values.put(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_SENSOR_ID, sensorId);
    values.put(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_TYPE,      type);
    values.put(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_VALUE,     value);
    values.put(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_TIMESTAMP,
               System.currentTimeMillis());

    // Returns the new row's _id, or -1 on error.
    return db.insert(
        SensorDbContract.SensorReading.TABLE_NAME,
        null,
        values
    );
}
```

**Explanation:**

- `db.insert(table, nullColumnHack, values)` ‚Äî the `nullColumnHack` is a workaround: SQLite does not allow inserting an entirely empty row; passing `null` here means "I am supplying all required columns" (or you pass `"column"` whose value becomes `NULL` if the `ContentValues` is empty).
- Wrapping inserts in transactions gives a massive speed boost (‚âà**100√ó faster** for bulk inserts) ‚Äî a common KTU viva question.

---

## 3.4 Step 4 ‚Äî READ (Querying with `Cursor`)

```java
public List<String> getAllTemperatureReadings(SQLiteDatabase db) {
    List<String> results = new ArrayList<>();

    String[] projection = {
        SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_VALUE,
        SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_TIMESTAMP
    };

    String selection    = SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_TYPE + " = ?";
    String[] selectionArgs = { "TEMP" };
    String sortOrder    = SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_TIMESTAMP + " DESC";

    Cursor cursor = db.query(
        SensorDbContract.SensorReading.TABLE_NAME, // table
        projection,                                  // columns to return
        selection,                                   // WHERE clause
        selectionArgs,                               // ?-replacements
        null,                                        // GROUP BY
        null,                                        // HAVING
        sortOrder                                    // ORDER BY
    );

    try {
        int valueCol = cursor.getColumnIndexOrThrow(
            SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_VALUE);
        int timeCol  = cursor.getColumnIndexOrThrow(
            SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_TIMESTAMP);

        while (cursor.moveToNext()) {
            double v  = cursor.getDouble(valueCol);
            long   ts = cursor.getLong(timeCol);
            results.add("Temp=" + v + " at " + ts);
        }
    } finally {
        cursor.close();   // ALWAYS close ‚Äî leaks are a common bug.
    }
    return results;
}
```

**Explanation:**

- `projection` = SELECT list; passing `null` means SELECT *.
- `selection` is the WHERE clause with `?` placeholders, and `selectionArgs` are the substitutions ‚Äî this prevents SQL injection.
- `getColumnIndexOrThrow(...)` is safer than `getColumnIndex(...)` because it throws if the column name is misspelled.
- The `try/finally` guarantees the cursor closes even if iteration throws.

---

## 3.5 Step 5 ‚Äî UPDATE and DELETE

```java
// UPDATE: Change sensor name for a given reading
public int renameSensor(SQLiteDatabase db,
                        long readingId,
                        String newSensorId) {

    ContentValues cv = new ContentValues();
    cv.put(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_SENSOR_ID, newSensorId);

    String selection    = SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_ID + " = ?";
    String[] args       = { String.valueOf(readingId) };

    return db.update(
        SensorDbContract.SensorReading.TABLE_NAME,
        cv,
        selection,
        args
    );
}

// DELETE: Clear out readings older than 7 days
public int purgeOldReadings(SQLiteDatabase db, long cutoffMillis) {
    String selection    = SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_TIMESTAMP + " < ?";
    String[] args       = { String.valueOf(cutoffMillis) };
    return db.delete(
        SensorDbContract.SensorReading.TABLE_NAME,
        selection,
        args
    );
}
```

**Explanation:**

- `update()` returns the **number of rows affected**, which you can use to confirm the WHERE matched something.
- `delete()` is similar ‚Äî if you pass `null` for `selection`, it deletes **every row** (catastrophic in production!).

---

## 3.6 Step 6 ‚Äî Transactional Bulk Insert (IoT-Batch Use Case)

When ingesting a batch of sensor readings every minute, wrap inserts in a transaction:

```java
public void bulkInsertReadings(SQLiteDatabase db, List<SensorReading> batch) {
    db.beginTransaction();
    try {
        for (SensorReading r : batch) {
            ContentValues cv = new ContentValues();
            cv.put(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_SENSOR_ID, r.sensorId);
            cv.put(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_TYPE,      r.type);
            cv.put(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_VALUE,     r.value);
            cv.put(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.COLUMN_TIMESTAMP, r.timestamp);
            db.insert(SensorDbContract.SensorReading.TABLE_NAME, null, cv);
        }
        db.setTransactionSuccessful();
    } finally {
        db.endTransaction();   // rolls back if setTransactionSuccessful() was not called.
    }
}
```

**Explanation:**

- Without a transaction, every `insert()` is auto-committed ‚Äî flushing to disk each time, which is **~100√ó slower**.
- `setTransactionSuccessful()` must be called before `endTransaction()`, otherwise the whole batch is rolled back.

---

