# üìò SECTION 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

---

## üÖ∞Ô∏è PART A ‚Äî Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### **Q1. [KTU University Exam ‚Äì May 2024]**
**Explain the role of `SQLiteOpenHelper` in Android. Why is it preferred over directly instantiating `SQLiteDatabase`?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

`SQLiteOpenHelper` is an **abstract helper class** in the `android.database.sqlite` package that manages the **creation, opening, and version upgrades** of an SQLite database. It encapsulates two lifecycle callback methods ‚Äî `onCreate(SQLiteDatabase db)` (invoked once when the `.db` file is created) and `onUpgrade(SQLiteDatabase db, int oldV, int newV)` (invoked when the schema version changes).

It is preferred over direct `SQLiteDatabase` instantiation because **(1)** it auto-handles the *check-if-file-exists* logic, **(2)** it centralizes schema DDL in one auditable place, **(3)** it provides safe migration paths via `onUpgrade()`, and **(4)** it exposes `getReadableDatabase()` and `getWritableDatabase()` which gracefully fall back to read-only mode when storage is full. Direct instantiation forces the developer to repeat DDL, handle versions manually, and risks data loss on upgrades.

---

### **Q2. [KTU University Exam ‚Äì Dec 2023]**
**Differentiate between `ContentValues` and `Cursor` in Android SQLite.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

`ContentValues` is a **write-side container** that holds key-value pairs representing one row of data to be passed into `insert()` or `update()`. It behaves like a `Map<String, Object>` and cannot store a null key; it represents *what you want to write*.

`Cursor`, in contrast, is a **read-side interface** that points to a row-set returned from `query()` or `rawQuery()`. It supports random access via `moveToFirst()`, `moveToNext()`, `moveToPosition()`, exposes type-safe getters (`getString`, `getInt`, `getDouble`), and must be closed with `close()` to free native resources.

In short ‚Äî **`ContentValues` is the input form; `Cursor` is the output slip.**

---

## üÖ±Ô∏è PART B ‚Äî Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each, with Internal Choice)

---

### **Question A ‚Äî 14 Marks**
**[KTU University Exam ‚Äì Sample Paper 2024, Module 3]**

**(a) [7 Marks]** With a neat block diagram, explain the architecture of SQLite in an Android application and describe how `SQLiteOpenHelper`, `SQLiteDatabase`, and `Cursor` interact during a typical SELECT query.

**(b) [7 Marks]** Design an SQLite schema for an IoT weather-monitoring mobile app that needs to store **sensor readings** (sensor ID, type, value, timestamp) and **device configurations** (device ID, location, sampling interval). Write the full `CREATE TABLE` statements and a Java helper class skeleton showing `onCreate` and `onUpgrade`.

---

### **Model Answer for Question A**

#### **Part (a) ‚Äî Architecture & SELECT Interaction [7 marks]**

The Android SQLite architecture is a **four-layer stack**:

| Layer | Component | Responsibility |
|---|---|---|
| L1 | Activity / Fragment | UI events trigger DB calls |
| L2 | Helper class (extends `SQLiteOpenHelper`) | Schema creation, versioning |
| L3 | `SQLiteDatabase` | Issue SQL statements, manage transactions |
| L4 | Native `libsqlite.so` + `.db` file | Actual data storage on internal storage |

**Interaction during a SELECT:**

1. The activity calls `myHelper.getReadableDatabase()`, which returns an `SQLiteDatabase` instance.
2. The activity calls `db.query(TABLE, projection, selection, args, null, null, sortOrder)` ‚Äî internally this is converted to a parameterized SQL string.
3. The SQLite engine executes the SELECT and returns a `Cursor` positioned **before the first row**.
4. The activity calls `cursor.moveToFirst()` or loops with `cursor.moveToNext()`.
5. For each row, column indices are obtained via `cursor.getColumnIndex("value")`, then values are read using type-safe getters like `cursor.getDouble(idx)`.
6. After iteration, `cursor.close()` releases the native cursor handle.

A detailed Mermaid diagram for this was shown in Section 4.1 above.

#### **Part (b) ‚Äî Schema Design for IoT Weather App [7 marks]**

```java
public final class WeatherDbContract {
    private WeatherDbContract() {}

    public static class SensorReading implements BaseColumns {
        public static final String TABLE              = "sensor_readings";
